        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1051</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001J</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001J.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue measure">Lebesgue measure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Lebesgue measure is the standard way of assigning a measure to subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, generalizing the intuitive notions of length, area, and volume to more complex sets. It is named after Henri Lebesgue.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For "nice" subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> (such as intervals in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, rectangles in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^2]]></fr:tex>, or rectangular solids in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^3]]></fr:tex>), the Lebesgue measure coincides with the standard notions of length, area, and volume. However, the Lebesgue measure can also be defined for a wide range of more complex and irregular sets.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Lebesgue measure has several important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>It is translation invariant: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(E + x) = m(E)]]></fr:tex> for any measurable set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It is scale invariant: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(\lambda  E) = |\lambda |^n m(E)]]></fr:tex> for any measurable set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[λ \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It is countably additive: If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{E_i\}]]></fr:tex> is a countable collection of pairwise disjoint measurable sets, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(\cup _i E_i) = \sum _i m(E_i)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It agrees with the standard notion of volume on "elementary sets" (e.g., rectangles)</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>The construction of Lebesgue measure typically involves defining the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001K.xml" addr="FA-001K" title="Lebesgue outer measure">Lebesgue outer measure</fr:link> first and then restricting it to the σ-algebra of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">Lebesgue measurable sets</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1053</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001K</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001K.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue outer measure">Lebesgue outer measure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue outer measure is a function that assigns an extended real number to any subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, serving as a precursor to the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001J.xml" addr="FA-001J" title="Lebesgue measure">Lebesgue measure</fr:link>, which is defined only on <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable sets</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, the Lebesgue outer measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E)]]></fr:tex> is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E) = \inf \{\sum _{i=1}^{\infty } |Q_i| : E \subseteq  \cup _{i=1}^{\infty } Q_i\}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the infimum is taken over all countable covers of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> by open rectangles <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q_i]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|Q_i|]]></fr:tex> denotes the volume (product of side lengths) of the rectangle <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q_i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Key properties of the Lebesgue outer measure include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>It is monotone: If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subseteq  F]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E) \leq  m^*(F)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It is countably subadditive: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(\cup _{i=1}^{\infty } E_i) \leq  \sum _{i=1}^{\infty } m^*(E_i)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It agrees with the standard notion of volume on rectangles</fr:li>
<fr:li>It is translation invariant: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E + x) = m^*(E)]]></fr:tex> for any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>The concept of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">Lebesgue measurability</fr:link> is defined in terms of the Lebesgue outer measure. A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable if and only if for any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(A) = m^*(A \cap  E) + m^*(A \setminus  E)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1055</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002A</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002A.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lp norm">Lp norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega  \subset  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> be a Lebesgue <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable set</fr:link>. For a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: \Omega  \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> we define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> as the (finite or infinite) number</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p(\Omega )} \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \left (\int _{\Omega } |f(x)|^p dx\right )^{1/p}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Moreover, we set</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \{\alpha  \in  \mathbb {R} : |f(x)| \leq  \alpha  \text { almost everywhere on } \Omega \}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> (also called the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Essential supremum">essential supremum</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>) is defined as</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^\infty (\Omega )} = \inf  C]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1057</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002D</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002D.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lp space">Lp space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subset  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable set</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex>. We call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex> the set of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable</fr:link> functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: E \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> such that</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p} < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Now, we set the following <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002B.xml" addr="FA-002B" title="Equivalence relation">equivalence relation</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f,g \in  \mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex>. We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \sim  g]]></fr:tex> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x) = g(x)]]></fr:tex> for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost every</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  E]]></fr:tex>. We set</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E) = \mathcal {L}^p(E)/\sim ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> is the quotient (vector) <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}^p(E)]]></fr:tex> through the relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sim ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a given <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0084">equivalence class</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f] \in  L^p(E)]]></fr:tex>, we define the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0018.xml" addr="FA-0018" title="Norm">norm</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f]]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p(E)}]]></fr:tex> for an arbitrary representative <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  [f]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>From now on, by abuse of notation, we shall confuse <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[f]]]></fr:tex> and its representative <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Note</fr:strong>: The elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces are not individual functions in the strictest sense, but rather <fr:strong>equivalence classes of functions</fr:strong>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1059</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001F</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001F.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_k : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [0, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be a sequence of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link>s. Assume that</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f_n(x) \leq  f_{n+1}(x) \quad  \text {almost everywhere}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Then, there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [0, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable</fr:link> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n \to  f]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link>, and</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\lim _{n \to  +\infty } \int  f_n(x)dx = \int  f(x)dx.}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1061</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001G</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001G.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Riesz-Fisher theorem">Riesz-Fisher theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subset  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable set</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex>. Then the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Moreover, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is a positive integer, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}_{n \in  \mathbb {N}}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000X.xml" addr="FA-000X" title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p(E)]]></fr:tex>, then there exist two functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f, h \in  L^p(E)]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000R.xml" addr="FA-000R" title="Subsequence">subsequence</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{n_k}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n]]></fr:tex> such that</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_{n_k}(x)| \leq  h(x)]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>,</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{n_k} \to  f]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p><fr:em>Note</fr:em>: The proof uses <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001E.xml" addr="FA-001E" title="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:link>, <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001F.xml" addr="FA-001F" title="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:link></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
