            <fr:title text="Lebesgue outer measure">Lebesgue outer measure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue outer measure is a function that assigns an extended real number to any subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, serving as a precursor to the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001J.xml" addr="FA-001J" title="Lebesgue measure">Lebesgue measure</fr:link>, which is defined only on <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable sets</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, the Lebesgue outer measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E)]]></fr:tex> is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E) = \inf \{\sum _{i=1}^{\infty } |Q_i| : E \subseteq  \cup _{i=1}^{\infty } Q_i\}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the infimum is taken over all countable covers of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> by open rectangles <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q_i]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|Q_i|]]></fr:tex> denotes the volume (product of side lengths) of the rectangle <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q_i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Key properties of the Lebesgue outer measure include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>It is monotone: If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subseteq  F]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E) \leq  m^*(F)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It is countably subadditive: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(\cup _{i=1}^{\infty } E_i) \leq  \sum _{i=1}^{\infty } m^*(E_i)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>It agrees with the standard notion of volume on rectangles</fr:li>
<fr:li>It is translation invariant: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E + x) = m^*(E)]]></fr:tex> for any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>The concept of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">Lebesgue measurability</fr:link> is defined in terms of the Lebesgue outer measure. A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable if and only if for any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(A) = m^*(A \cap  E) + m^*(A \setminus  E)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
